prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Orion B North
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: 3mm continuum and CO (1-0) for each source in Orion B North, single pointings

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Correlator setup: For the CO (1-0) observations, we configure one specral window of the ALMA correlator to 305 km/s bandwidth and 0.184 km/s spectral resolution. This is sufficient to cover and resolve the expected velocity range of outflows from protostars and VeLLOs (maximum velocity range of roughly 10 km/s, minimum velocity range of roughly 2 km/s). The continuum emission will be measured in three spectral windows of 2 GHz bandwidth and 31 MHz channels (per SPW).
Resolution and largest angular scale: The cores in our survey have a typical size of 16", but sub-structures will be (by definition) much smaller than this. We ask for 1.125" resolution and 10" largest angular scale, sufficient to resolve protostellar outflows, hidden protostars, and sufficient to search for substructure in these cores. The requested angular resolution is designed to match the linear resolution of our Cycle 1 program to observe cores in Chamaeleon I.
Sensitivity: We base our sensitivity requirements on our observations of very low luminosity objects in Perseus and the expected 3mm brightness of the typical dense core. Taking the average core mass, radius, and temperature, we find the brightness per 1.125" beam if the mass were distributed uniformly. We want to detect point sources with column desnities 10x the mean to find all VeLLOs, and this will also allow us to be sensitive to all significant substructures.

prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Ophiuchus
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: 3mm continuum and CO (1-0) for each source in Ophiuchus, single pointings

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Correlator setup: For the CO (1-0) observations, we configure one specral window of the ALMA correlator to 305 km/s bandwidth and 0.184 km/s spectral resolution. This is sufficient to cover and resolve the expected velocity range of outflows from protostars and VeLLOs (maximum velocity range of roughly 10 km/s, minimum velocity range of roughly 2 km/s). The continuum emission will be measured in three spectral windows of 2 GHz bandwidth and 31 MHz channels (per SPW).
Resolution and largest angular scale: The cores in our survey have a typical size of 31", but sub-structures will be (by definition) much smaller than this. We ask for 3" resolution and 10" largest angular scale, sufficient to resolve protostellar outflows, hidden protostars, and sufficient to search for substructure in these cores. The requested angular resolution is designed to match the linear resolution of our Cycle 1 program to observe cores in Chamaeleon I.
Sensitivity: We base our sensitivity requirements on our desire to use ALMA resources efficiently and avoid spending significantly more time on calibrations than observing the science targets. We find that spending 1 minute per pointing splits the science and calibration time evently, providing us with 20 sigma detections of ~1 mJy VeLLOs and 20 sigma detections of significant sub-structures in the core. Furthermore, we expect CO (1-0) line brightness of 2 K with a line width of at least 2 km/s, well matched to the 0.35K rms expected in 0.5 km/s channel in our observations of Ophiuchus.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Recent interferometric surveys of starless cores have found that 1) 5-20% of these objects actually harbor low-luminosity star-forming objects, and 2) none of the truly starless cores have any detectable substrucure or evidence for fragmentation. These surveys, however, were intentionally biased and suffer from small sample sizes. To begin to address this problem, we have an approved (highest priority) ALMA Cycle 1 survey of all starless and protostellar cores in the Chamaeleon I molecular cloud, a region of low-mass and isolated star formation. Here we propose to carry out a similar survey of all known cores in the Ophiuchus and Orion B North moelcular clouds, the nearest star-forming regions with very different physical conditions than Chamaeleon I. This survey will enable the first accurate, uniform, and high resolution census of dense cores in a range of environments. We will determine definitive classifications (starless or protostellar) and discriminate between models of star formation that predict different paths for the origin of binary protostellar systems. We will test the extent to which the environment in different clouds influences the path(s) of star formation.
